<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1925-10-26T11:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1925-10-26T11:00:00-05:00" n="22" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d22">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">500.A12/73: Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Germany</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Schurman</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                                State</gloss></hi></head>
                        <opener><seg rendition="#center">[Paraphrase]</seg></opener>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Berlin</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1925-10-26T17:00:00+01:00"><hi rend="italic">October 26,
                                        1925—5 p.m.</hi></date><lb/>[Received 5:34
                            p.m.]</dateline></opener>
                        <p>183. Department’s circular telegram, October 22, 4 p.m.<note n="22" xml:id="d22fn22">See footnote 15, <ref target="#pg_11">p.
                                11</ref>.</note> President’s remarks have received exceedingly
                            little press comment here; only article of any interest is in <hi rend="italic">Vossische Zeitung</hi> of October 23.</p>
                        <p rend="center">. . . . . . . . . . . . . .</p>
                        <pb facs="0141" n="15" xml:id="pg_15"/>
                        <p>I believe, however, that German opinion in general for obvious reasons
                            would welcome call from President Coolidge for disarmament conference at
                            Washington.</p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Schurman</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>